05838nam a22007695i 9780824891596DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212022hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021023727  a97808248915967 a10.1515/97808248915962doi  a(DE-B1597)585125  a(OCoLC)1291507036  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aDS904b.H6713 2021 4aDS904 7aHIS0230002bisacsh04a951.9223/eng00aRecord of the Seasonal Customs of Korea :bTongguk sesigi by Toae Hong Sŏk-mo /ced. by Robert E. Buswell. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKorean Classics Library: Historical Materials ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tChronology -- tI. Translator’s Introduction -- tTranslator’s Introduction -- tII. Translation Record of the Seasonal Customs of Korea (Tongguk sesigi) -- tPreface -- tFirst Lunar Month -- tSecond Month -- tThird Month -- tFourth Lunar Month -- tFifth Month -- tSixth Month -- tSeventh Month -- tEighth Month -- tNinth Month -- tTenth Month -- tEleventh Month -- tTwelfth Month -- tIntercalary Month -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Rituals, Customs, and Games -- tIndex of Government, Offices, and Titles -- tIndex of Geographic Names (Administrational Units) and Place-Names Mentioned in the Tongguk sesigi -- tIndex of Food, Beverages, and Ingredients -- tAbout the Translator0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecord of the Seasonal Customs of Korea (Tongguk sesigi) is one of the most important primary sources for anyone interested in traditional Korean cultural and social practices. The manuscript was completed in 1849 by Toae Hong Sŏk-mo, a wealthy poet and scholar from an influential family. Toae, with his keen interest in the habits and customs of both courtiers and commoners, compiled in almanac form (he divided his book into chronological sections by lunar and intercalary months) a comprehensive record of seasonal palace events, rituals, entertainment, and food and drink consumed on high days and holidays, as well as information on farm work and traditions. Nineteenth-century Korean intellectuals possessed a deep understanding of Chinese history and culture together with a growing awareness of the distinctiveness of Korea’s past and traditions. Toae’s work reflects this in the many comparisons he makes between the habits and customs of the two countries, "ing literary and philosophical sources to note similarities and contrasts. Knowledge of the seasonal traditions he describes was largely forgotten over the generations as Korea rapidly modernized, but in recent years much effort has been made to recover this wisdom: Tongguk sesigi is now widely read and referenced as a popular source for details on traditional food, customs, and entertainment.While an ever-increasing number of books introducing Korean culture written by non-Koreans or Koreans researching their roots is now available, Record of the Seasonal Customs of Korea contains information “from the source” that also reveals the mindset and penchants of a premodern Korean intellectual. Readers will thus be confronted with many concepts, names, and ideas not readily understandable so extensive notes are provided in this translation. Those studying other Asian cultures with some Chinese influence will also find valuable insights here for cross-cultural comparison and research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFolklorezKorea. 0aSeasonszKoreavFolklore. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh1 aBuswell, Robert E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCha-yu, Yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo